\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 PROLOGUE
\par 
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 NOT ONCE IN A GENERATION DID THE VOICE OF THE CITY
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 change as it was changing now. Day and night, age after
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 age, it had never faltered. To myriads of men it had been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the first and the last sound they had ever heard It was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 part of the city: when it ceased the city would be dead
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and the desert sands would be settling in the great streets
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of Diaspar.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Even here, half a mile above the ground, the sudden
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hush brought Convar out to the balcony. Far below, the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 moving ways were stil\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 l sweeping between the great buildings,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 but now they were thronged with silent crowds Something
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had drawn the languid people of the city from their homes: in their thousands they were drifting slowly between
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the cliffs of colored metal. And then Convar saw\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  that all
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 those myriads of faces were turned towards the sky
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 For a moment fear crept into his soul--fear lest after all
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 these ages the Invaders had come again to Earth. Then
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he too was staring at the sky, entranced by a wonder he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had never hoped to see aga\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in. He watched for many minutes
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 before he went to fetch his infant son.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The child Alvin was frightened at first. The soaring spires
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the city, the moving specks two thousand feet below--
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 these were part of his world, but the thing in the sky was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 beyond a\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ll his experience. It was larger than any of the city's
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 buildings, and its whiteness was so dazzling that it hurt the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 eye. Though it seemed to be solid, the restless winds were
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 changing its outlines even as he watched.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Once, Alvin knew, the skies of Earth \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had been filled with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 strange shapes. Out of space the great ships had come,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 bearing unknown treasures, to berth at the Port of Diaspar
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 But that was half a billion years ago; before the beginning
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of history the Port had been buried by the drifting sand
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 5
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 6 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Convar's voice was sad when presently he spoke to his
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 son.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Look at it well, Alvin," he said. "It may be the last the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 world will ever know. I have only seen one other in all my
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 life, and once they filled the skies of Earth."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 y watched in silence, and with them all the thousands
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in the streets and towers of Diaspar, until the last cloud
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 slowly faded from sight, sucked dry by the hot, parched air
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the unending deserts.
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 I
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 THE PRISON OF DIASPAR
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 THE LESSON WAS FINISHED. THE DRO\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 WSY WHISPER OF T::E
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hypnone rose suddenly in pitch and ceased abruptly on a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 thrice repeated note of command. Then the machine blurred
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and vanished, but still Alvin sat staring into nothingness
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 while his mind slipped back through the ages to meet reality
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ag\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ain.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Jeserac was the Erst to speak: his voice was worried and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a little uncertain.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Those are the oldest records in the world, Alvin--the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 only ones that show Earth as it was before the Invaders
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 came. Very few people indeed have ever seen them."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Slowly the b\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 oy turned towards his tutor. There was something
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in his eyes that worried the old man, and once again
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Jeserac regretted his action. He began to talk quickly, as if
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 trying to set his own conscience at ease.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "You know that we never talk about the ancient times,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and I only showed you those records because you were so
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 anxious to see them. Don't let them upset you: as long as
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 we're happy, does it matter how much of the world we
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 occupy? The people you have been wa\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tching had more space,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 but they were less contented than we."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Was that true? -Alvin wondered. He thought once more
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the desert lapping round the island that was Diaspar, and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his mind returned to the world that Earth had been. He saw
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 again the endless lea\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 gues of blue water, greater than the land
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 itself, rolling their waves against golden shores. His ears were
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 still ringing with the boom of breakers stilled these thousand
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 million years. And he remembered the forests and prairies,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and the strange beasts that\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  had once shared the world with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Man.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 All this was gone. Of the oceans, nothing remained but
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 9
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 )0 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the grey deserts of salt, the winding sheets of Earth. Salt
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and sand, from Pole to Pole, with only the lights of Diaspar
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 burning in \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the wilderness that must one day overwhelm them.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 And these were the least of the things that Man had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 lost, for above the desolation the forgotten stars were shining
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 still.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Jeserac," said Alvin at last, "once I went to the Tower
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of Loranne. No one lives th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ere any more, and I could look
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 out over the desert. It was dark, and I couldn't see the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ground, but the sky was full of colored lights. I watched them for a long time, but they never moved. So presently
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 I came away. Those were the stars, weren't they?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Jeserac was alarmed. Exactly how Alvin had got to the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Tower of Loranne was a matter for further investigation.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The boy's interests were becoming--dangerous.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Those were the stars," he answered briefly. "What of them?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "We used to visit them once, didn't we\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 A long pause. Then, "Yes."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Why did we stop? What were the Invaders?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Jeserac rose to his feet. His answer echoed back through
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 all the teachers the world had ever known.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "That's enough for one day, Alvin. Later, when you are
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 elder, I'll tell you more--b\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ut not now. You already know
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 too much."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin never asked the question again: later, he had no
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 need for the answer was clear. And there was so much in
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar to beguile the mind that for months he could forget that strange yearning he alone seemed to feel.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar was a world in itself. Here Man had gathered
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 all his treasures, everything that had been saved from the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ruin of the past. All the cities that had ever been had given
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 something to Diaspar: even before the coming of the Invaders
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 its name had been k\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 nown on the worlds that Man had lost.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Into the building of Diaspar had gone all the skill, all
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the artistry of the Golden Ages. When the great days were
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 coming to an end, men of genius had remoulded the city
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and given it the machines that made it immortal.\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  Whatever
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 might be forgotten, Diaspar would live and bear the descendants
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of Man safely down the stream of Time.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 They were, perhaps, as contented as any race the world
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had known, and after their fashion they were happy. They
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 spent their long lives amid beauty that had never been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 surpassed, for the labour of millions of centuries had been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 dedicated to the glory of Diaspar.
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 11
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 This was Alvin's world, a world which for ages had been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sinking into a graci\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ous decadence. Of this Alvin was still
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 unconscious, for the present was so full of wonder that it
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was easy to forget the past. There was so much to do, so
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 much to learn before the long centuries of his youth ebbed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 away.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Music had been the first of the arts\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  to attract him, and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 for a while he had experimented with many instruments.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 But this most ancient of all arts was now so complex that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 it might take a thousand years for him to master all its secrets,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and in the end he abandoned his ambitions. He could list\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 en,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 but he could never create.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 For a long time the thought-converter gave him great delight.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 On its screen he shaped endless patterns of form and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 color, usually copies--deliberate or otherwise--of the ancient
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 masters. More and more frequently he found hims\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 elf creating
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 dream landscapes from the vanished Dawn World, and often
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his thoughts turned wistfully to the records that Jeserac had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shown him. So the smoldering flame of his discontent burned
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 slowly towards the level of consciousness, though as yet he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 scarcely worried by the vague restlessness he often felt
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 But through the months and the years, that restlessness
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was growing. Once Alvin had been content to share the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 pleasures and interests of Diaspar, but now he knew that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 they were not sufficient. His horizons were expanding, and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the knowledge that all his life must be bounded by the walls
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the city was becoming intolerable to him. Yet he knew
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 well enough that there was no alternative, for the wastes
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the desert covered\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  all the world.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He had seen the desert only a few times in his life, but
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he knew no one else who had ever seen it at all. His people's
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fear of the outer world was something he could not understand:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to him it held no terror, but only mystery. When he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was we\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ary of Diaspar, it called to him as it was calling now.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The moving ways were glittering with life and color as
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the people of the city went about their affairs. They smiled
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 at Alvin as he worked his way to the central highspeed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 section. Sometimes they greet\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ed him by name: once it had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 been flattering to think that he was known to the whole of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar, but now it gave him little pleasure.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 In minutes the express channel had swept him away from
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the crowded heart of the city, and there were few people
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in sight wh\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 en it came to a smooth halt against a long platform
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of brightly colored marble. The moving ways were so much
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a part of his life that Alvin had never imagined any other
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 12 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 form of transport. An engineer of the ancient world would
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 have gone slowly mad trying to understand how a solid roadway
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 could be Exed at both ends while its centre travelled at
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a hundred miles an hour One day Alvin might be puzzled
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 too, but for the present he accepted his environment as
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 uncritically as all the other citizens of Diaspar,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 This area of the city was almost deserted. Although the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 population of Diaspar had not altered for millenia, it was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the custom for families to move at frequent intervals. One
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 day the tide of life would swee\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 p this way again, but the great
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 towers had been lonely now for a hundred thousand years.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The marble platform ended against a wall pierced with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 brilliantly lighted tunnels. Alvin selected one without hesitation
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and stepped into it. The peristaltic field sei\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 zed him at
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 once and propelled him forward while he lay back luxuriously,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 watching his surroundings.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It no longer seemed possible that he was in a tunnel far
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 underground. The art that had used all Diaspar for its
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 canvas had been busy here, and above Alvin t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he skies seemed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 open to the winds of heaven. All around were the spires
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the city, gleaming in the sunlight. It was not the city
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 as he knew it, but the Diaspar of a much earlier age. Although
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 most of the great buildings were familiar, there were subtle
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 d\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ifferences that added to the interest of the scene. Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 wished he could linger, but he had never found any way of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 retarding his progress through the tunnel.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 All too soon he was gently set down in a large elliptical
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 chamber, completely surrounded by windo\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ws. Through these
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he could catch tantalizing glimpses of gardens ablaze with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 brilliant flowers. There were gardens still in Diaspar, but
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 these had existed only in the mind of the artist who conceived
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 them. Certainly there were no such flowers as these
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in the world today.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin stepped through one of the windows--and the illusion
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was shattered. He was in a circular passageway curving steeply
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 upwards. Beneath his feet the floor began to creep slowly
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 forward, as if eager to lead him to his goal. He walked \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a few
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 paces until his speed was so great that further effort would
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 be wasted.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The corridor still inclined upwards, and in a few hundred
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 feet had curved through a complete right-angle. But only
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 logic knew this: to the senses it was now as if one were
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 being \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hurried along an absolutely level corridor. The fact that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he was in reality travelling up a vertical shaft thousands of
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 13
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 feet deep gave Alvin no sense of insecurity, for a failure of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the polarizing Eeld was unthinkable.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Present\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ly the corridor began to slope "downwards" again
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 until once more it had turned through a right-angle. The
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 movement of the floor slowed imperceptibly until it came
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to rest at the end of a long hall lined with mirrors. Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was now, he knew, almost at the s\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ummit of the Tower of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Loranne.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He lingered for a while in the hall of mirrors, for it had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a fascination that was unique. There was nothing like it,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 as far as Alvin knew, in the rest of Diaspar. Through some
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 whim of the artist, only a few of the mirrors ref\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 lected the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 scene as it really was--and even those, Alvin was convinced,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 were constantly changing their position. The rest certainly
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 reflected something, but it was faintly disconcerting to see
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 oneself walking amid everchanging and quite imaginary surroundings.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin wondered what he would do if he saw
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 anyone else approaching him in the mirror-world, but so far
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the situation had never arisen.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Five minutes later he was in a small, bare room throug\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 h
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 which a warm wind blew continually. It was part of the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tower's ventilating system, and the moving air escaped
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 through a series of wide openings that pierced the wall of the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 building. Through them one could get a glimpse of the world
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 beyond Diaspar.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It wa\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 s perhaps too much to say that Diaspar had been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 deliberately built so that its inhabitants could see nothing
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the outer world. Yet it was strange that from nowhere
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 else in the city, as far as Alvin knew, could one see the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 desert. The outermost towers of \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar formed a wall around
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the city, turning their backs upon the hostile world beyond,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and Alvin thought again of his people's strange reluctance
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to speak or even to think of anything outside their little
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 universe.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Thousands of feet below, the sunlight \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was taking leave
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the desert. The almost horizontal rays made a pattern of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 light against the eastern wall of the little room, and Alvin's
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 own shadow loomed enormous behind him. He shaded his
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 eyes against the glare and peered down at the land upon
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 which n\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 o man had walked for unknown ages.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 There was little to see: only the long shadows of the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sand-dunes and, far to the west, the low range of broken
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hills beyond which the sun was setting. It was strange to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 think that of all the millions of living men, he alone had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 seen this sight.
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 14 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 There was no twilight: with the going of the sun, night
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 swept like a wind across the desert, scattering the stars before
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 it. High in the south burned \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a strange formation that had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 puzzled Alvin before--a perfect circle of six colored stars,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 with a single white giant at its center. Few other stars had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 such brilliance, for the great suns that had once burned
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 so fiercely in the glory of youth were now gutte\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ring to their
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 doom.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 For a long time Alvin knelt at the opening, watching the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 stars fall towards the west. Here in the glimmering darkness,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 high above the city, his mind seemed to be working with a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 supernormal clarity. There were still tremendous gaps in hi\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 s
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knowledge, but slowly the problem of Diaspar was beginning
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to reveal itself.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The human race had changed--and he had not. Once, the curiosity and the desire for knowledge which cut him
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 off from the rest of his people had been shared by all the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 world. Far \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 back in time, millions of years ago, something
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 must have happened that had changed mankind completely.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Those unexplained references to the Invaders--did the answer
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 lie there?
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It was time he returned. As he rose to leave, Alvin was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 suddenly struck by a thou\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ght that had never occurred to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 him before. The air-vent was almost horizontal, and perhaps
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a dozen feet long. He had always imagined that it ended
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in the sheer wall of the tower, but this was a pure assumption.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 There were, he realized now, several other possibilities.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Indeed, it was more than likely that there would be a ledge
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of some kind beneath the opening, if only for reasons of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 safety. It was too late to do any exploring now, but tomorrow
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he would come again\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 . . . .
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He was sorry to have to lie to Jeserac, but if the old man
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 disapproved of his eccentricities it was only kindness to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 conceal the truth. Exactly what he hoped to discover, Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 could not have said. He knew perfectly well that if by any
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 means he suc\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ceeded in leaving Diaspar, he would soon have
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to return. But the schoolboy excitement of a possible adventure
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was its own justification.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It was not difficult to work his way along the tunnel,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 though he could not have done it easily a year before. The
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 thoug\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ht of a sheer five-thousand-foot drop at the end worried
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin not at all, for Man had completely lost his fear of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 heights. And, in fact, the drop was only a matter of a yard
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 on to a wide terrace running right and left athwart the face
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the tower.
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 AGAIN\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ST THE FALL OF NIGHT 15
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin scrambled out into the open, the blood pounding
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in his veins. Before him, no longer framed in a narrow
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 rectangle of stone, lay the whole expanse of the desert. Above,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the face of the tower still soared hundreds of feet into th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sky. The neighboring buildings stretched away to north and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 south, an avenue of titans. The Tower of Loranne, Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 noted with interest, was not the only one with air-vents
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 opening towards the desert. For a moment he stood drinking
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in the tremendous landscape: then he began to examine
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the ledge on which he was standing.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It was perhaps twenty feet wide, and ended abruptly in
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a sheer drop to the ground. Alvin, gazing fearlessly over the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 edge of the precipice, judged that the desert was\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  at least a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 mile below. There was no hope in that direction.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Far more interesting was the fact that a flight of steps led
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 down from one end of the terrace, apparently to another
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ledge a few hundred feet below. The steps were cut in
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the sheer face of the bu\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ilding, and Alvin wondered if they
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 led all the way to the surface. It was an exciting possibility:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in his enthusiasm, he overlooked the physical implications
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of a five-thousand-foot descent.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 But the stairway was little more than a hundred feet long.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It Cam\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e to a sudden end against a great block of stone that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 seemed to have been welded across it. There was no way
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 past: deliberately and thoroughly, the route had been barred.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin approached the obstacle with a sinking heart. He
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had forgotten the sheer imposs\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ibility of climbing a stairway
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a mile high, if indeed he could have completed the descent,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and he felt a baffled annoyance at having come so far only
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to meet with failure.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He reached the stone, and for the first time saw the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 message engraved upon it. The l\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 etters were archaic, but
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he could decipher them easily enough. Three times he read
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the simple inscription: then he sat down on the great stone
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 slabs and gazed at the inaccessible land below.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 THERE IS A BETTER WAY.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 GIVE MY GREETINGS TO THE KEEPER OF THE RECORDS.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alaine of Lyndar
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 2
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 START OF THE SEARCH
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 RORDEN, KEEPER OF THE RECORDS, CONCEALED HIS SURPRISE
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 when his visitor announced himself. He recognized Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 at once and even as the boy was entering had punched out
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his name on the information machine. Three seconds later,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin's personal card was lying in his hand.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 According to Jeserac, the duties of the Keeper of the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Records were somewhat obscure, but Alvin had expected to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 find him in the heart of an enormous filin\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 g system. He had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 also\hich\f39 \emdash \loch\f39 for no reason at all\hich\f39 \emdash \loch\f39 expected to meet someone quite
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 as old as Jeserac. Instead, he found a middle-aged man in a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 single room containing perhaps a dozen large machines. Apart
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 from a few papers strewn across the desk, there were no
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 recor\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ds of any kind to be seen.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden's greeting was somewhat absent-minded, for he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was surreptitiously studying Alvin's card.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Alaine of Lyndar?" he said. "No, I've never heard of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 him. But we can soon find who he was."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin watched with interest while he pun\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ched a set
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of keys on one of the machines. Almost immediately there
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 came the glow of a synthesizer field, and a slip of paper
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 materialized.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Alaine seems to have been a predecessor of mine\hich\f39 \emdash \loch\f39 a very
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 long time ago. I thought I knew all the Keepers for the last
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hundred million years, but he must have been before that.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It's so long ago that only his name has been recorded, with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 no other details at all. Where was that inscription?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "In the Tower of Loranne," said Alvin after a moment's
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hesitation.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Another set of keys was punched, but this time the field
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 did not reappear and no paper materialized.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 19
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 20 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "What are you doing?" asked Alvin. "Where are all your
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 records?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The Keeper laughed.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "That always puzzles people. It would\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  be impossible to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 keep written records of all the information we need: it's
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 recorded electrically and automatically erased after a certain
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 time, unless there's a special reason for preserving it. If
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alaine left any message for posterity, we'll soon discove\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 r it."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "How?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "There's no one in the world who could tell you that.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 All I know is that this machine is an Associator. If you give
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 it a set of facts, it will hunt through the sum total of human
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knowledge until it correlates them."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Doesn't that take a lot o\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 f time?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Very often. I have sometimes had to wait twenty years
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 for an answer. So won't you sit down?" he added, the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 crinkles round his eyes belying his solemn voice.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin had never met anyone quite like the Keeper of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the Records, and he decided that he l\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 iked him. He was tired
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of being reminded that he was a boy, and it was pleasant
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to be treated as a real person.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Once again the synthesizer field flickered and Rorden
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 bent down to read the slip. The message must have been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a long one, for it took him several minutes to finish it.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Finally he sat down on one of the room's couches, looking
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 at his visitor with eyes which, as Alvin noticed for the first
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 time, were of a most disconcerting shrewdness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs20\insrsid12586992 \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "What does it say?" he burst o\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ut at last, unable to contain
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his curiosity any longer.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden did not reply. Instead, he was the one to ask for
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 information.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Why do you want to leave Diaspar?" he said quietly.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 If Jeserac or his father had asked him that question, Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 would have found \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 himself floundering in a morass of half-
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 truths or downright lies. But with this man, whom he had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 iret for only a few minutes, there seemed none of the barriers
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Aat had cut him off from those he had known all his life.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I'm not sure," he said, speaking slo\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 wly but readily. "I've
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 always felt like this. There's nothing outside Diaspar, I know
\par \loch\af39\dbch\af31505\hich\f39 \emdash \loch\f39 but I want to go there all the same."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He looked shyly at Rorden, as if expecting encouragement,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 but the Keeper's eyes were far away. When at last he again
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 turned to Alvi\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 n, there was an expression on his face that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the boy could not fully understand, but it held a tinge of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sadness that was somewhat disturbing.
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 21
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 No one could have told that Rorden had come to the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 greatest crisis in his life. For thousands of years he had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 carried out his duties as the interpreter of the machines,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 duties requiring little initiative or enterprise. Somewhat apart
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 from the tumult of the city, rather aloof from his fellows,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden had li\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ved a happy and contented life. And now this
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 boy had come, disturbing the ghosts of an age that had been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 dead for millions of centuries, and threatening to shatter his
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 cherished peace of mind.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 A few words of discouragement would be enough to destroy
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 reat, but looking into the anxious, unhappy eyes,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden knew that he could never take the easy way. Even
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 without the message from Alaine, his conscience would have
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 forbidden it.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Alvin," he began, "I know there are many things that have been puzzling you.\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  Most of all, I expect, you have
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 wondered why we now live here in Diaspar when once the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 whole world was not enough for us."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin nodded, wondering how the other could have read
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his mind so accurately.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Well, I'm afraid I cannot answer that question comple\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tely.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Don't look so disappointed: I haven't finished yet.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It all started when Man was Eghting the Invaders--whoever
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 or whatever they were. Before that, he had been expanding
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 through the stars, but he was driven back to Earth in wars
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of which we have no con\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ception. Perhaps that defeat changed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his character, and made him content to pass the rest of his
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 existence on Earth. Or perhaps the Invaders promised to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 leave him in peace if he would remain on his own planet:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 we don't know. All that is certain is that he \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 started to develop
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 an intensely centralized culture, of which Diaspar was the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 6nal expression.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "At first there were many of the great cities, but in the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 end Diaspar absorbed them all, for there seems to be some
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 force driving men together as once it drove them to the stars.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Few people ever recognize its presence, but we all have a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fear of the outer world, and a longing for what is known and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 understood. That fear may be irrational, or it may have some
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 foundation in\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  history, but it is one of the strongest forces
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in our lives."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Then why don't I feel that way?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "You mean that the thought of leaving Diaspar, where
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 you have everything you need and are among all your friends,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 doesn't fill you with something like horror?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "No."
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 22 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The Keeper smiled wryly.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I'm afraid I cannot say the same. But at least I can
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 appreciate your point of view, even if I cannot share it. Once I might have felt doubtful about helping you, but not now
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that I've seen Alai\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ne's message."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "You still haven't told me what it was!"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden laughed.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I don't intend to do so until you're a good deal older.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 But I'll tell you what it was about.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Alaine foresaw that people like you would be born in
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 future ages: he realized that they m\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ight attempt to leave
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar and he set out to help them. I imagine that whatever
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 way you tried to leave the city, you would meet an
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 inscription directing you to the Keeper of the Records.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Knowing that the Keeper would then question his machines,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alaine left a message, buried safely among the thousands and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 millions of records that exist. It could only be found if the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Associator was deliberately looking for it. That message directs
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 any Keeper to assist the enquirer, even if he disapproves of his que\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 st. Alaine believed that the human race was becoming
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 decadent, and he wanted to help anyone who might regenerate
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 it. Do you follow all this?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin nodded gravely and Rorden continued.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I hope he was wrong. I don't believe that humanity is
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 decadent--it's s\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 imply altered. You, of course, will agree with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alaine--but don't do so simply because you think it's fine
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to be different from everyone else! We are happy: if we have lost anything, we're not aware of it.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Alaine wrote a good deal in his message, but the i\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 mportant
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 part is this. There are three ways out of Diaspar. He does
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 not say where they lead, nor does he give any clues as to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 how they can be found, though there are some very obscure
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 references I'll have to think about. But even if what he says
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 is true, y\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ou are far too young to leave the city. Tomorrow
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 I must speak to your people. No, I won't give you away! But
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 leave me now--I have a good deal to think about."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden felt a little embarrassed by the boy's gratitude.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 When Alvin had gone, he sat for a while \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 wondering if, after
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 all, he had acted rightly.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 There was no doubt that the boy was an atavism--a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 throwback to the great ages. Every few generations there
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 still appeared minds that were the equal of any the ancient
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 days had known. Born out of their time, th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ey could have
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 little influence on the peacefully dreaming world of Diaspar.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The long, slow decline of the human will was too far ad\page AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 23
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 vanced to be checked by any individual genius, however
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 brilliant. After a few centuries of restlessness, the variants
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 accepted their fate and ceased to struggle against it. When
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin understood his position, would he too realize that his
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 only hope of happiness lay in conforming with the world?
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden wondered\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  if, after all, it might not have been kinder
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in the long run to discourage him. But it was too late now:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alaine had seen to that.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The ancient Keeper of the Records must have been a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 remarkable man, perhaps an atavism himself. How many
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 times down the ages h\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ad other Keepers read that message
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of his and acted upon it for better or worse? Surely, if there
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had been any earlier cases, some record would have been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 made.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden thought intently for a moment: then, slowly at
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 first, but soon with mounting conEdence, h\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e began to put
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 question after question to the machines, until every Associator
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in the room was running at full capacity. By means now
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 beyond the understanding of man, billions upon billions of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 facts were racing through the scrutinizers. There was nothing
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 o do but to wait. . . .
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 IN AFTER YEARS, ALVIN WAS OFTEN TO MARVEL AT HIS GOOD
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fortune. Had the Keeper of the Records been unfriendly, his
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 quest could never have begun. But Rorden, in spite of the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 years between them, shared something of his own curiosity.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 I\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 n Rorden's case, there was only the desire to uncover lost
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knowledge: he would never have used it, for he shared with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the rest of Diaspar that dread of the outer world which
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin found so strange. Close though their friendship became,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that barrier was always to lie between them.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin's life was now divided into two quite distinct portions.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He continued his studies with Jeserac, acquiring the immense
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and intricate knowledge of people, places and customs without
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 which no one could play a\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ny part in the life of the city.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Jeserac was a conscientious but a leisurely tutor, and with so
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 many centuries before him he felt no urgency in completing
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his task. He was, in fact, rather pleased that Alvin should
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 have made friends with Rorden. The Keeper\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  of the Records
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was regarded with some awe by the rest of Diaspar, for he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 alone had direct access to all the knowledge of the past.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 How enormous and yet how incomplete that knowledge
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was, Alvin was slowly learning. In spite of the self-cancelling
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 24 AGAIN\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 circuits which obliterated all information as soon as it was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 obsolete, the main registers contained a hundred trillion facts
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 at the smallest estimate. Whether there was any limit to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the capacity of the machines Rorden did not know: tha\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 t
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knowledge was lost with the secret of their operation.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The Associators were a source of endless wonder to Alvin,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 who would spend hours setting up questions of their keyboards.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It was amusing to discover that people whose names
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 began with "S" had a tenden\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 cy to live in the eastern part
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the city--though the machines hastened to add that the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fact had no statistical signiEcance. Alvin quickly accumulated
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a vast array of similar useless facts which he employed to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 impress his friends. At the same time, under Rorden's
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 guidance, he was learning all that was known of the Dawn
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Ages, for Rorden had insisted that it would need years of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 preparation before he could begin his quest. Alvin had recognized
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the truth of this, th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ough he sometimes rebelled against
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 it. But after a single attempt, he abandoned any hope of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 acquiring knowledge prematurely.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He had been alone one day when Rorden was paying
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 one of his rare visits to the administrative centre of the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 city. The temptation ha\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 d been too strong, and he had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ordered the Associators to hunt for Alaine's message.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 When Rorden returned, he found a very scared boy trying
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to discover why all the machines were paralyzed. To Alvin's
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 immense relief, Rorden had only laughed and punched a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 se\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ries of combinations that had cleared the jam. Then he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 turned to the culprit and tried to address him severely.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Let that be a lesson to you, Alvin! I expected something
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 like this, so I've blocked all the circuits I don't want you to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 explore. That block wi\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ll remain until I think it's safe to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 lift it."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin grinned sheepishly and said nothing. Thereafter he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 made no more excursions into forbidden realms.
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 3
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 THE TOMB OF YARLAN ZEY
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 NOT FOR THREE YEARS DID RORDEN MAKE MORE THAN CASUAL
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 references to the purpose\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  of their world. The time had passed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 quickly enough, for there was so much to learn and the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knowledge that his goal was not unattainable gave Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 patience. Then, one day when they were struggling to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 reconcile two conflicting maps of the ancient world, the main
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Associator suddenly began to call for attention.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden hurried to the machine and returned with a long
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sheet of paper covered with writing. He ran through it
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 quickly and looked at Alvin with a \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 smile.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "We will soon know if the Erst way is still open," he said
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 quietly.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin jumped from his chair, scattering maps in all directions.
\par 
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Where is it?" he cried eagerly.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden laughed and pushed him back into his seat.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I haven't kept you waiting all t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his time because I wanted
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to," he said. "It's true that you were too young to leave
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar before, even if we knew how it could be done. But
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that's not the only reason why you had to wait. The day
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 you came to see me, I set the machines searching through
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he records to discover if anyone after Alaine's time had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tried to leave the city. I thought you might not be the first, and I was right. There have been many others: the last was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 about fifteen million years ago. They've all been very careful
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to leave us no\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  clues, and I can see Alaine's influence there.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 In his message he stressed that only those who searched for
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 themselves should be allowed to find the way, so I've had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to explore many blind avenues. I knew that the secret had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 been hidden carefully--yet not s\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 o carefully that it couldn't
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 be found.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 27
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 28 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "About a year ago I began to concentrate on the idea of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Transport. It was obvious that Diaspar must have had many
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 links with the rest of the world, and although the Port itself
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 has been buried by the desert for ages, I thought that there
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 might be other means of travel. Right at the beginning I
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 found that the Associators would not answer direct questions:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alaine must have put a block on them just as I once did for
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 your benefit. Un\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fortunately I can't remove Alaine's block, so I've had to use indirect methods.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "If there was an external transport system, there's certainly
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 no trace of it now. Therefore, if it existed at all, it has
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 been deliberately concealed. I set the Associators to \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 investigate
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 all the major engineering operations carried out in the city
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 since the records began. This is a report on the construction
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the central park--and AJaine has added a note to it himself. As soon as it encountered his name, of course, the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 machin\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e knew it had finished the search and called for me."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden glanced at the paper as if rereading part of it
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 again. Then he continued:--
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "We've always taken it for granted that all the moving
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ways should converge on the Park: it seems natural for them
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to d\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 o so. But this report states that the Park was built after
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the founding of the city--many millions of years later, in tact. Therefore the moving ways once led to something the"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "An airport, perhaps?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "No: flying was never allowed over any city, except in ^\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ery ancient times, before the moving ways were built. Even
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar is not as old as thati But listen to Alaine's note:--
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 " 'When the desert buried the Port of Diaspar, the emergency
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 system which had been built against that day was able
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to carry the remaini\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ng transport. It was finally closed down
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 by Yarlan Zey, builder of the Park, having remained almost
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 unused since the Migration.' "
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin looked rather puzzled.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "It doesn't tell me a great deal," he complained.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden smiled. "You've been letting the Associators do
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 too much thinking for you," he admonished gently. "Like
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 all of Alaine's statements, it's deliberately obscure lest the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 wrong people should learn from it. But I think it tells us
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 quite enough. Doesn't t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he name "Yarlan Zey" mean anything
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to you?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I think I understand," said Alvin slowly. "You're talking
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 about the Monument?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Yes: it's in the exact centre of the Park. If you extended
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 29
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the moving ways, they would all meet there\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 . Perhaps, once
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 upon a time, they did."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin was already on his feet.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Let's go and have a look," he exclaimed.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden shook his head.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "You've seen the Tomb of Yarlen Zey a score of times
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and noticed nothing unusual about it. Before we rush off,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 don't you\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  think it would be a good idea to question the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 machines again?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin was forced to agree, and while they were waiting
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 began to read the report that the Associator had already produced.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Rorden," he said at-last, "what did Alaine mean when
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he spoke about t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he Migration?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "It's a term often used in the very earliest records," answered
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden. "It refers to the time when the other cities
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 were decaying and all the human race was moving towards
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Then this 'emergency system,' whatever it is, leads to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 them?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Almost certainly."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin meditated for a while.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "So you think that even if we do find the system, it will
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 only lead to a lot of ruined cities?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I doubt if it will even do that," replied Rorden. "When
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 they were abandoned, the machines were closed d\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 own and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the desert will have covered them by now."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin refused to be discouraged.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "But Alaine must have known that!" he protested. Rorden
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shrugged his shoulders.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "We're only guessing," he said, "and the Associator hasn't
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 any information at the moment. It\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  may take several hours,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 but with such a restricted subject we should have all the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 recorded facts before the end of the day. We'll follow your
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 advice after all."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The screens of the city were down and the sun was shining
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fiercely, though its rays would have\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  felt strangely weak to a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 man of the Dawn Ages. Alvin had made this journey a hundred
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 times before, yet now it seemed almost a new adventure.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 When they came to the end of the moving way, he bent
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 down and examined the surface that had carried them through
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he city. For the first time in his life, he began to realize
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 something of its wonder. Here it was motionless, yet a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hundred yards away it was rushing directly towards him faster
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 than a man could run.
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 30 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden was watching him, but he misunderstood the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 boy's curiosity.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "When the park was built," he said, "I suppose they had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to remove the last section of the way. I doubt if you'll learn
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 anything from it."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I wasn't thinking of that," said Alvin. "I was won\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 dering
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 how the moving ways work."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden looked astonished, for the thought had never occurred
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to him. Ever since men had lived in cities, they had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 accepted without thinking the multitudinous services that lay
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 beneath their feet. And when the cities had be\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 come completely
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 automatic, they had ceased even to notice that they
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 were there.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Don't worry about that," he said. "I can show you a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 thousand greater puzzles. Tell me how my Recorders get
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 their information, for example."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 So, without a second thought, Rorde\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 n dismissed the moving
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ways--one of the greatest triumphs of human engineering.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The long ages of research that had gone to the making of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 anisotropic matter meant nothing to him. Had he been told
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that a substance could have the properties of a solid in one
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 dimension and of a liquid in the other two, he would not
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 even have registered surprise.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The Park was almost three miles across, and since every
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 pathway was a curve of some kind all distances were considerably
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 exaggerated. When he had been younger Alvin had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 spent a great deal of time among the trees and plants of this
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 largest of the city's open spaces. He had explored the whole
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of it at one time or another, but in later years much of its
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 charm had vanished. Now he understood why: he had seen
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the ancient reco\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 rds and knew that the Park was only a pale
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shadow of a beauty that had vanished from the world.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 They met many people as they walked through the avenues
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of ageless trees and over the dwarf, perennial grass that never
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 needed trimming. After a while they grew\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  tired of acknowledging
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 greetings, for everyone knew Afvin and almost everyone
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knew the Keeper of the Records. So they left the paths
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and wandered through quiet byways almost overshadowed by
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 trees. Sometimes the trunks crowded so closely round them
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e great towers of the city were hidden from sight.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and for a little while Alvin could imagine he was in the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ancient world of which he had so often dreamed.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The Tomb of Yarlan Zey was the only building in the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Park. An avenue of the eternal trees led up the \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 low hill
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 on which it stood, its rose-pink columns gleaming in the sun\page AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 31
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 light. The roof was open to the sky, and the single chamber
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was paved with great slabs of apparently natural stone. But
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 for geological ages human feet had cr\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ossed and recrossed that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 floor and left no trace upon its inconceivably stubborn material.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin and Rorden walked slowly into the chamber, until
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 they came face to face with the statue of Yarlan Zey.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The creator of the great park sat with slightly downcast
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 eyes, as if examining the plans spread across his knees. His
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 face wore that curiously elusive expression that had baffled
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the world for so many generations. Some had dismissed it as
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 no more than a whim of the artist's, but to others it seemed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that Yarlan Zey was smiling at some secret jest. Now Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knew that they had been correct.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden was standing motionless before the statue, as if
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 seeing it for the first time in his life. Presently he walked
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 back a few yards and began to examine the grea\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 t flagstones.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "What are you doing?" asked Alvin.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Employing a little logic and a great deal of intuition,"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 replied Rorden. He refused to say any more, and Alvin
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 resumed his examination of the statue. He was still doing
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 this when a faint sound behind him at\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tracted his attention.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden, his face wreathed in smiles, was slowly sinking into
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the floor. He began to laugh at the boy's expression.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I think I know how to reverse this," he said as he disappeared.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "If I don't come up immediately, you'll have to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 pull \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 me out with a gravity polarizer. But I don't think it will
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 be necessary."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The last words were muffled, and, rushing to the edge
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the rectangular pit, Alvin saw that his friend was already
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 many feet below the surface. Even as he watched, the shaft
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 deepene\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 d swiftly until Rorden had dwindled to a speck no longer recognizable as a human being. Then, to Alvin's relief,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the far-off rectangle of light began to expand and the pit
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shortened until Rorden was standing beside him once more.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 For a moment there was a p\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 rofound silence. Then Rorden
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 smiled and began to speak.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Logic," he said, "can do wonders if it has something to
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 work upon. This building is so simple that it couldn't conceal
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 anything, and the only possible secret exit must be through
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the floor. I argued that it would be marked in some way,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 so I searched until I found a slab that differed from all the rest."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin bent down and examined the floor.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "But it's just the same as all the others!" he protested.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden put his hands on the boy'\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 s shoulders and turned
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 32 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 him round until he was looking towards the statue. For a
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 moment Alvin stared at it intently. Then he slowly nodded
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his head.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I see," he whispered. "So that is the secret of Yarian
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Zey!"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The eyes of the \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 statue were fixed upon the floor at his feet. There was no mistake. Alvin moved to the next slab,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and found that Yarian Zey was no longer looking towards
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 him.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Not one person in a thousand would ever notice that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 unless they were looking for it," said Rorde\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 n, "and even, then, it would mean nothing to them. At first I felt rather
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 foolish myself, standing on that slab and going through
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 different combinations of control thoughts. Luckily the circuits
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 must be fairly tolerant, and the code-thought turned out
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to b\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e "Alaine of Lyndar." I tried "Yarian Zey" at first, but
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 it wouldn't work, as I might have guessed. Too many people
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 would have operated the machine by accident if that trigger
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 thought had been used."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "It sounds very simple," admitted Alvin, "but I don't th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ink I would have found it in a thousand years. Is that how the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Associators work?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden laughed.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Perhaps," he said. "I sometimes reach the answer before
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 they do, but they always reach it." He paused for a moment.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 We'll have to leave the shaft open: no one is likely to fall down it."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 As they sank smoothly into the earth, the rectangle of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sky dwindled until it seemed very small and far away. The
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shaft was lit by a phosphorescence that was part of the walls,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and seeme\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 d to be at least a thousand feet deep. The walls
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 were perfectly smooth and gave no indication of the machinery
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that had lowered them.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The doorway at the bottom of the shaft opened automatically
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 as they stepped towards it. A few paces took them
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 through the \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 short corridor--and then they were standing,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 overawed by its immensity, in a great circular cavern whose
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 walls came together in a graceful, sweeping curve three hundred
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 feet above their heads. The column against which they
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 were standing seemed too slender \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to support the hundreds
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of feet of rock above it. Then Alvin noticed that it did not
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 seem an integral part of the chamber at all, but was clearly of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 much later construction. Rorden had come to the same conclusion.
\par 
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "This column," he said, "was built simply\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  to house the
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 35
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shaft down which we came. We were right about the moving
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ways--they all lead into this place."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin had noticed, without realizing what they were, the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 great tunnels that pierced the circumference of the chamber
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He could see that they sloped gently upwards, and now he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 recognized the familiar grey surface of the moving ways
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Here, far beneath the heart of the city, converged the wonderful
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 transport system that carried all the traffic of Diaspar.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 But these were only the severed stumps of the great roadways:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the strange material that gave them life was now frozen into
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 immobility.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin began to walk towards the nearest of the tunnels. He had gone only a few paces when he realized that something
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 happening to the ground beneath his feet. It was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 becoming transparent. A few more yards, and he seemed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to be standing in mid-air without any visible support. He Stopped and stared down into the void beneath.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Rorden!" he called. "Come and look at this!"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e other joined him, and together they gazed at the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 marvel beneath their feet. Faintly visible, at an indefinite
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 depth, lay an enormous map--a great network of lines converging
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 towards a spot beneath the central shaft. At first it
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 seemed a confused maze, bu\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 t after a while Alvin was able
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to grasp its main outlines. As usual, he had scarcely begun
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his own analysis before Rorden finished his.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "The whole of this floor must have been transparent once,"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 said the Keeper of the Records. "When this chamber was sealed\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  and the shaft built, the engineers must have done
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 something to make the center opaque. Do you understand
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 what it is, Alvin?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I think so," replied the boy. "It's a map of the transport
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 system, and those little circles must be the other cities of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Earth. I \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 can just see names beside them, but they're too faint
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to read."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "There must have been some form of internal illumination
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 once," said Rorden absently. He was looking towards the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 walls of the chamber.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I thought so!" he exclaimed. "Do you see how all these
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 radiating lines lead towards the small tunnels?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin had noticed that besides the great arches of the moving
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ways there were innumerable smaller tunnels leading out
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the chamber--tunnels that sloped downwards instead of up.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden continued without wai\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ting for a reply.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "It was a magnificent system. People would come down
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 34 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the moving ways, select the place they wished to visit, and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 then follow the appropriate line on the map."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "And what happens then?" said Alvin.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 As usual, Ro\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 rden refused to speculate.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I haven't enough information," he answered. "I wish
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 we could read the names of those citiesi" he complained,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 changing the subject abruptly.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin had wandered away and was circumnavigating the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 central pillar. Presently his voice\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  came to Rorden, slightly
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 muffled and overlaid with echoes from the walls of the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 chamber.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "What is it?" called Rorden, not wishing to move as he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had nearly deciphered one of the dimly visible groups of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 characters. But Alvin's voice was insistent, so he wen\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 t to join
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 him.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Far beneath was the other half of the great map, its faint
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 web-work radiating towards the points of the compass. But
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 this time not all of it was too dim to be clearly seen, for one
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the lines, and one only, was brilliantly illuminated. It
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 seemed to have no connection with the rest of the system, and pointed like a gleaming arrow to one of the downward-
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sloping tunnels. Near its end the line transfixed a circle of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 golden light, and against that circle was the single word
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 LYS." That was all.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 For a long time Alvin and Rorden stood gazing down at that silent symbol. To Rorden it was no more than another
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 question for his machines, but to Alvin its promise was boundless.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He tried to imagine this great chamber as it had been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in the ancient days, wh\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 en air transport had come to an end
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 but the cities of Earth still had commerce one with the other.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He thought of the countless millions of years that had passed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 with the traffic steadily dwindling and the lights on the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 great map dying one by one, until at \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 last only this single
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 line remained. He wondered how long it had gleamed there
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 among its darkened companions, waiting to guide the steps
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that never came, until at last Yarlan Zey had sealed the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 moving ways and closed Diaspar against the world.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 That had bee\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 n hundreds of millions of years ago. Even
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 then, Lys must have lost touch with Diaspar. It seemed impossible
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that it could have survived: perhaps, after all, the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 map meant nothing now.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rorden broke into his reverie at last. He seemed a little
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 nervous and il\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 l at ease.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "It's time we went back," he said. "I don't think we
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 should go any further now."
