\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the world\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 , was a line of stone which would have
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 dwarfed the mightiest giants of Diaspar. It was so far away
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that its details were blurred by sheer distance, but there was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 something about its outlines that Alvin found puzzling. Then
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his eyes became at last accustome\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 d to the scale of that colossal
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 landscape, and he knew that those far-off walls had not
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 been built by Man.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Time had not conquered everything: Earth still possessed
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 mountains of which she could be proud.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 For a long time Alvin stood at the mouth of the tunne\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 l,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 growing slowly accustomed to the strange world in which he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had found himself. Search as he might, nowhere could he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 see any trace of human life. Yet the road that led down the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 hillside seemed well-kept: he could do no more than accept
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 its guidance.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 At th\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e foot of the hill, the road disappeared between great
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 trees that almost hid the sun. As Alvin walked into their
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shadow, a strange medley of scents and sounds greeted him.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The rustle of the wind among the leaves he had known before,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 but underlying that were a thousand vague noises that
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 conveyed nothing to his mind. Unknown odors assailed him,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 smells that had been lost even to the memory of his race.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The warmth, the profusion of scent and color, and the unseen
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 presences of a million li\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ving things, smote him with almost
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 physical violence.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 He came upon the lake without any warning. The trees
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to the right suddenly ended, and before him was a great expanse
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of water, dotted with tiny islands. Never in his life
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had Alvin seen such quantities \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the precious liquid: he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 walked to the edge of the lake and let the warm water trickle
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 through his fingers.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The great silver fish that suddenly forced its way through
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the underwater reeds was the first non-human creature he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had ever seen. As it hung in n\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 othingness, its fins a faint blur
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of motion, Alvin wondered why its shape was so startlingly
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 familiar. Then he remembered the records that Jeserac had
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 shown him as a child, and knew where he had seen those
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 graceful lines before. Logic told him that the res\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 emblance
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 could only be accidental--but logic was wrong.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 All through the ages, artists had been inspired by the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 urgent beauty of the great ships driving from world to world
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Once there had been craftsmen who had worked, not with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 crumbling metal or decaying s\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tone, but with the most im\page AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 47
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 perishable of all materials--flesh and blood and bone. Though
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 they and all their race had been utterly forgotten, one of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 their dreams had survived the ruins of cities and the wreck
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of continents.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 At last Alvin broke the lake's enchantment and continued
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 along the winding road. The forest closed around him once
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 more, but only for a little while. Presently the road ended,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in a great clearing perhaps half a mile wide and twice as long.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Now Alvin unders\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tood why he had seen no trace of man
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 before.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The clearing was full of low, two-storied buildings, colored
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 in soft shades that rested the eye even in the full glare of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the sun. They were of clean, straightforward design, but several
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 were built in a complex \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 architectural style involving the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 use of fluted columns and gracefully fretted stone. In these
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 buildings, which seemed of great age, the immeasurably ancient
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 device of the pointed arch was used.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 As he walked slowly towards the village, Alvin was still
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 stru\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ggling to grasp his new surroundings. Nothing was familiar:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 even the air had changed. And the tall, golden-haired
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 people coming and going among the buildings were very different
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 from the languid citizens of Diaspar.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin had almost reached the village whe\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 n he saw a group
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of men coming purposefully towards him. He felt a sudden,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 heady excitement and the blood pounded in his veins. For
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 an instant there flashed through his mind the memory of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 all Man's fateful meetings with other races. Then he. came
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to a halt\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 , a few feet away from the others.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 They seemed surprised to see him, yet not as surprised as
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he had expected. Very quickly he understood why. The leader
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of the party extended his hand in the ancient gesture of
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 friendship.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "We thought it best to meet you here," he said. "Our
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 home is very different from Diaspar, and the walk from the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 terminus gives visitors a chance to become--acclimatized."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin accepted the outstretchd hand, but for a moment
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was too astonished to reply.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Y\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ou knew I was coming?" he gasped at length.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "We always know when the carriers start to move. But we did not expect anyone so young. How did you discover
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the way?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I think we'd better restrain our curiosity, Gerane. Seranis
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 is waiting."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The name "Seranis" \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was preceded by a word unfamiliar
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 48 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to Alvin. It somehow conveyed an impression of affection,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 tempered with respect.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Gerane agreed with the speaker and the party began to move into the village. As they walked, Alvin studied the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 faces around him. They appeared kindly and intelligent:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 there were none of the signs of boredom, mental strife, and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 faded brilliance he might have found in a similar group in
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 his own city. To his broadening mind, it seemed that they
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 possessed all that his \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 own people had lost. When they smiled,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 which was often, they revealed lines of ivory teeth--the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 pearls that Man had lost and won and lost again in the long
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 story of evolution.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The people of the village watched with frank curiosity as
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin followed his gui\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 des. He was amazed to see not a few
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 children, who stared at him in grave surprise. No other single
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fact brought home to him so vividly his remoteness from
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the world he knew. Diaspar had paid, and paid in full, the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 price of immortality.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The party halted before the largest building Alvin had yet
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 seen. It stood in the center of the village and from a flagpole
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 on its small circular tower a green pennant floated along the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 breeze.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 All but Cerane dropped behind as he entered the building.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Insid\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 e it was quiet and cool: sunlight filtering through the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 translucent walls lit up everything with a soft, restful glow.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The floor was smooth and resilient, inlaid with fine mosaics.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 On the walls, an artist of great ability and power had depicted
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a set of fo\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 rest scenes. Mingled with these paintings
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 were other murals which conveyed nothing to Alvin's mind,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 yet were attractive and pleasant to look upon. Let into the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 wall was something he had hardly expected to see--a visi-
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 phone receiver, beautifully made, its \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 idle screen filled with
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a maze of shifting colors.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 They walked together up a short circular stairway that led
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 them out on the flat roof of the building. From this point,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the entire village was visible and Alvin could see that it consisted
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of about a hundre\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 d buildings. In the distance the trees
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 opened out into wide meadows: he could see animals in
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 some of the fields but his knowledge of biology was too slight
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 for him to guess at their nature.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 In the shadow of the tower, two people were sitting together
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 at a \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 desk, watching him intently. As they rose to greet
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 him, Alvin saw that one was a stately, very handsome woman
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 whose golden hair was shot through with wisps of grey. This,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he knew, must be Seranis. Looking into her eyes, he could
\par \page \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT 49
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sense that wisdom and depth of experience he felt when he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was with- Rorden and, more rarely, with Jeserac.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The other was a boy a little older than himself in appearance,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and Alvin needed no second glance to tell that Seranis
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 mu\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 st be his mother. The clear-cut features were the same,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 though the eyes held only friendliness and not that almost
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 frightening wisdom. The hair, too, was different--black instead
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 of gold--but no-one could have mistaken the relationship
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 between them.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Feelin\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 g a little overawed, Alvin turned to his guide for sup- port--but Gerane had already vanished. Then Seranis smiled,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 and his nervousness left him.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Welcome to Lys," she said. "I am Seranis, and this is my
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 son Theon, who will one day take my place. You are t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 he
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 youngest who has ever come to us from Diaspar: tell me
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 how you found the way."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Haltingly at Erst, and then with increasing confidence,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin began his story. Theon followed his words eagerly, for
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Diaspar must have been as strange to him as Lys had been
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 to Alvin. But Seranis, Alvin could see, knew all that he was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 telling her, and once or twice she asked questions which
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 showed that in some things at least her knowledge went
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 beyond his own. When he had finished there was silence for
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 a while. Then Seranis lo\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 oked at him and said quietly:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Why did you come to Lys?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "I wanted to explore the world," he replied. "Everyone
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 told me that there was only desert beyond the city, but I
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 wanted to make sure for myself."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 The eyes of Seranis were full of sympathy and even sadness
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 when she spoke again:
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "And was that the only reason?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Alvin hesitated. When he answered, it was not the explorer
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 who spoke, but the boy not long removed from childhood.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "No," he said slowly, "it wa\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 sn't the only reason, though
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 I did not know until now. I was lonely."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Lonely? In Diaspar?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Yes," said Alvin. "I am the only child to be born there
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 for seven thousand years."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Those wonderful eyes were still upon him and, looking
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 into their depths, Alvin h\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ad the sudden conviction that Se- ranis could read his mind. Even as the thought came, he saw
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 an expression of amused surprise pass across her face--and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 knew that his guess had been correct. Once both men and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 machines had possessed this power, and the unch\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 anging ma\page 50 AGAINST THE FALL OF NIGHT
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 chines could still read their master's orders. But in Diaspar,
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Man himself had lost the gift he had given to his slaves.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Rather quickly, Seranis broke into his thoughts.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "If you are looking for life," she said, "your \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 search has
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 ended. Apart from Diaspar, there is only desert beyond our
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 mountains."
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 It was strange that Alvin, who had questioned accepted
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 beliefs so often before, did not doubt the words of Seranis.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 His only reaction was one of sadness that all his teaching
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 had been so nearly true.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Tell me something about Lys," he asked. "Why have
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 you been cut off from Diaspar for so long, when you know
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 all about us?"
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Seranis smiled at his question.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "It's not easy to answer that in a few words, but I'll do
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 my best.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Because you have lived in Diaspar all your life, you have
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 come to think of Man as a city-dweller. That isn't true, Al-
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 vin. Since the machines gave us freedom, there has always
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 been a rivalry between two different types of civilization. In
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 the Dawn Ages t\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 here were thousands of cities, but a large
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 part of mankind lived in communities like this village of ours.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "We have no records of the founding of Lys, but we know
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 that our remote ancestors disliked city life intensely and
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 would have nothing to do with it. \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 In spite of swift and universal transport, they kept themselves largely apart from the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 rest of the world and developed an independent culture which
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 was one of the highest the race had ever known.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Through the ages, as we advanced along our different
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 roads,\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39  the gulf between Lys and the cities widened. It was
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 bridged only in times of great crisis: we know that when the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 Moon was falling, its destruction was planned and carried out
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 by the scientists of Lys. So too was the defense of Earth
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 against the Invaders, \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 whom we held at the Battle of Shalmirane.
\par 
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "That great ordeal exhausted mankind: one by one the
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 cities died and the desert rolled over them. As the population
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 fell, humanity began the migration which was to make Dia-
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 spar the last and greatest of all citie\hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 s.
\par \hich\af39\dbch\af31505\loch\f39 "Most of these changes passed us by, but we had our own
